> My garbage disposal won't run and the dishwasher-- which has a tube to the disposal-- is also clogged. I assume these are related. Is this something I can fix on my own?
**assistant**:
> Yes, James, you should be able to tackle this problem on your own, given that it's not too severe. Here's a step-by-step approach you can try:
> 
> 1. **Check the power:** Make sure the disposal is plugged in and the breaker hasnâ€™t tripped.
> 
> 2. **Press the reset button:** Garbage disposals have a red or black reset button on the bottom that can start the motor back up.
> 
> 3. **Check for obstructions:** Turn off the garbage disposal at the wall switch and unplug it, then look inside the device for foreign objects that may be causing it to jam. Use pliers or tongs to remove any obstructions -- never your hand.
> 
> 4. **Try to manually turn the blades:** If you could not find any visible obstructions, you could try moving the blades manually with a hex key from underneath the unit (this typically requires a 1/4" hex key). Once the blades can be moved slightly, switch on the power again and see if it starts up. 
> 
> 5. **Check the dishwasher hose:** If your garbage disposal is running but the dishwasher is still clogged, inspect the hose from your dishwasher to your disposal. It might be clogged. If so, detach it, clean it out, then re-attach it (turn off power during this step).
> 
> It's important to remember to be careful whenever dealing with electrical appliances and if the problem persists, call a professional. You don't want to risk damaging your appliances or being injured.
> 
> Relatedly, it's a good practice to keep your disposal blades sharp. You can do this by regularly grinding small pieces of ice and eggshells, which help clean the blades. Always run cold water when you're grinding to solidify any grease that may be present so it can be chopped and flushed through the system.
